01:25:56,679 --> 01:25:59,944
I kinda like walking from time to time.

1139
01:26:00,016 --> 01:26:02,849
I stay on my feet all the time at work.

1140
01:26:02,919 --> 01:26:06,355
I just can't find shoes
that's comfortable.

1141
01:26:06,422 --> 01:26:10,654
Hospital shoes might be
the answer. Nurse's shoes.

1142
01:26:10,727 --> 01:26:13,491
Or the kind old ladies wear who
work in the school cafeteria.

1143
01:26:13,563 --> 01:26:16,088
Same difference.

1144
01:26:16,166 --> 01:26:18,862
I get real mean when my feet hurt.

1145
01:26:18,935 --> 01:26:22,371
It's the only time I don't
like checking out customers,

1146
01:26:22,438 --> 01:26:25,305
when my feet hurt.

1147
01:26:25,375 --> 01:26:30,403
You and Karl aren't talking much.
You boys must really like that food.

1148
01:26:30,480 --> 01:26:33,643
Well, I ain't got nothing to say
- anything about shoes.

1149
01:26:33,716 --> 01:26:36,310
Listen, everybody. I...

1150
01:26:36,386 --> 01:26:39,378
This might sound corny, but, um...

1151
01:26:40,390 --> 01:26:43,382
I've had a few glasses of wine, and
that tends to make me a little emotional,

1152
01:26:43,459 --> 01:26:45,427
but I'm gonna say it anyway.

1153
01:26:45,495 --> 01:26:48,089
It came over me in a rush.

1154
01:26:48,164 --> 01:26:50,655
I just want all of you to know

1155
01:26:50,700 --> 01:26:54,898
that I care about each and
every person at this table.

1156
01:26:55,905 --> 01:26:59,466
Thank you, Vaughan. That's really
sweet of you. We care about you, too.

1157
01:26:59,542 --> 01:27:01,908
- Don't we, y'all?
- Oh, yeah.

1158
01:27:01,978 --> 01:27:05,778
Also, Melinda, please don't
tell anyone at the store

1159
01:27:05,848 --> 01:27:08,783
that Albert was here tonight.

1160
01:27:10,587 --> 01:27:12,578
OK?

1161
01:27:13,823 --> 01:27:15,620
Why?

1162
01:27:15,692 --> 01:27:21,688
Well, you know how this town is. People
talk and they spread these cruel rumors.

1163
01:27:21,764 --> 01:27:26,997
Unfortunately, there are certain parts
of my life I have to keep private.

1164
01:27:27,070 --> 01:27:31,507
You mean about you and Albert
being together in that way?

1165
01:27:31,574 --> 01:27:32,563
Yeah. Yes.

1166
01:27:32,642 --> 01:27:35,509
I think everybody at
the store already knows.

1167
01:27:35,578 --> 01:27:37,842
They're always talking about it.

1168
01:27:37,914 --> 01:27:41,315
Maureen Ledbetter told
the most awful story

1169
01:27:41,384 --> 01:27:44,979
about why you ain't allowed at
the First Baptist Church no more.

1170
01:27:45,054 --> 01:27:50,082
Karl, why don't you and Melinda
go take a walk? It's nice out.

1171
01:27:55,231 --> 01:27:57,392
All right, then.

1172
01:28:06,943 --> 01:28:09,537
- The food sure
is good. - Mm-hm.

1173
01:28:15,952 --> 01:28:19,046
- You walk fast, don't you?
- I reckon.

1174
01:28:21,958 --> 01:28:25,758
These are the worst
shoes I own for walking.

1175
01:28:25,828 --> 01:28:28,319
How far did you say you wanted to go?

1176
01:28:28,364 --> 01:28:31,856
I don't reckon I thought
about it too much.

1177
01:28:33,503 --> 01:28:37,064
I don't know, Karl. She
just ain't catching fire.

1178
01:28:37,140 --> 01:28:39,472
Did you check them points?

1179
01:28:40,777 --> 01:28:43,041
No. No, I didn't.

1180
01:28:43,112 --> 01:28:45,273
That's probably it.

1181
01:28:47,116 --> 01:28:49,607
- (Bill) Yes, ma'am.
- (Melinda.) Is Karl here?

1182
01:28:49,652 --> 01:28:51,984
(Bill) Yeah. Just a minute.

1183
01:28:54,924 --> 01:28:57,415
Hey, Karl, there's somebody
out here to see you.

1184
01:28:57,493 --> 01:29:00,553
Some gal holding a nice bouquet.

1185
01:29:00,630 --> 01:29:05,567
Come on, now, she wants to talk
to you. Don't just sit there.

1186
01:29:18,848 --> 01:29:21,442
Hi, Karl, I'm on my lunch break.

1187
01:29:22,518 --> 01:29:25,510
These were on sale
'cause they're not fresh.

1188
01:29:25,588 --> 01:29:29,786
$ 2.99 a bunch plus my ten
percent employee discount.

1189
01:29:30,793 --> 01:29:35,423
Since I didn't bring nothing
for you on our date last night,

1190
01:29:35,498 --> 01:29:38,490
I thought you might like to have 'em.

1191
01:29:45,942 --> 01:29:47,773
Thank you.

1192
01:29:47,844 --> 01:29:50,244
Scooter, let's you and me
go over to the Frostee Cream

1193
01:29:50,313 --> 01:29:52,645
- and pick up something for lunchtime.
- Oh, well, I can go.

1194
01:29:52,715 --> 01:29:54,580
You don't have to. You don't never go.

1195
01:29:54,650 --> 01:29:57,448
Goddamnit, Scooter, come on. Let's go.

1196
01:29:57,520 --> 01:29:59,852
Pardon my language, ma'am.

1197
01:30:04,026 --> 01:30:07,860
Darlin'

1198
01:30:09,232 --> 01:30:11,894
Lord above me

1199
01:30:15,671 --> 01:30:18,663
Well, I just thought I'd bring you 'em.

1200
01:30:19,609 --> 01:30:21,770
I liked walking with you.

1201
01:30:21,844 --> 01:30:25,780
I got a blister the size
of a quarter on one heel.

1202
01:30:27,517 --> 01:30:28,950
Well...

1203
01:30:29,018 --> 01:30:31,612
I'll see you sometime, I guess.

1204
01:30:37,226 --> 01:30:39,922
A blister sure can hurt. Mm-hm.

1205
01:30:41,931 --> 01:30:43,455
Yeah.

1206
01:30:47,737 --> 01:30:49,762
Flowers is purdy.

1207
01:30:49,839 --> 01:30:52,239
I've always thought that. Mm-hm.

1208
01:30:55,278 --> 01:30:57,439
Me, too.

1209
01:31:00,917 --> 01:31:04,751
Then you fix me a cup of tea

1210
01:31:05,988 --> 01:31:10,322
Darlin'. You're so damn swweet

1211
01:31:13,763 --> 01:31:16,596
Don't forget the milk

1212
01:31:19,469 --> 01:31:22,802
And wwherever! Go

1213
01:31:25,675 --> 01:31:28,838
And wwhatever! Do

1214
01:31:30,847 --> 01:31:34,180
Darlin'

1215
01:31:35,985 --> 01:31:38,647
! love you

1216
01:31:47,296 --> 01:31:50,561
Hey, Karl, how did you
know I was in the garage?

1217
01:31:50,633 --> 01:31:52,828
I seen that door
cracked open a little bit

1218
01:31:52,902 --> 01:31:55,928
and I figured you was in
there fooling around. Mm-hm.

1219
01:31:56,005 --> 01:31:58,496
- You off of work?
- Yes, sir.

1220
01:31:58,574 --> 01:32:01,372
Where'd you get them flowers?

1221
01:32:01,444 --> 01:32:04,743
That gal that made employee of
the month at the Dollar Store,

1222
01:32:04,814 --> 01:32:08,011
she gave 'em to me for walking with her.

1223
01:32:09,252 --> 01:32:11,686
I was going over to the secret place.

1224
01:32:11,754 --> 01:32:15,121
I borrowed one of your
books. You ain't mad, are you?

1225
01:32:15,191 --> 01:32:18,058
No, sir. You can look at any
one of my books you want to.

1226
01:32:18,127 --> 01:32:21,585
Thank you. It's name's
A Christmas Carol.

1227
01:32:21,664 --> 01:32:25,464
That's that one on Christmas
I was telling you about.

1228
01:32:25,535 --> 01:32:28,504
Well, you wanna go with me?

1229
01:32:28,571 --> 01:32:30,334
All right, then.

1230
01:32:30,406 --> 01:32:32,203
Yeah. Come on.

1231
01:32:32,275 --> 01:32:34,436
All right.

1232
01:32:40,883 --> 01:32:43,215
(Frank) You know why I want
you to play ball with me?

1233
01:32:43,286 --> 01:32:44,514
(Karl) No.

1234
01:32:44,587 --> 01:32:48,114
(Frank) 'Cause it's fun. It
don't matter if you ain't no good.

1235
01:32:48,190 --> 01:32:50,681
It takes your mind off everything else,

1236
01:32:50,760 --> 01:32:53,695
and when you're running real
fast trying to score a touchdown,

1237
01:32:53,763 --> 01:32:56,288
that's all you're thinking about.

1238
01:32:56,365 --> 01:33:00,199
I ain't no account, but Daddy
always said he was proud of me

1239
01:33:00,269 --> 01:33:03,329
when I threw the ball or ran with it.

1240
01:33:03,406 --> 01:33:07,809
Did you have any brothers and
sisters, growing up, to play with?

1241
01:33:07,877 --> 01:33:10,141
I had one there for a little bit,

1242
01:33:10,947 --> 01:33:13,142
but, uh...

1243
01:33:13,215 --> 01:33:16,343
it didn't get old enough for
me to play with it. Mm-hm.

1244
01:33:16,419 --> 01:33:18,751
Why not? It died?

1245
01:33:18,821 --> 01:33:20,755
Yes, sir.

1246
01:33:20,823 --> 01:33:23,348
Why?

1247
01:33:23,426 --> 01:33:26,020
It got born a little too early.

1248
01:33:26,462 --> 01:33:31,559
My mother and father, they made it
come out too early some way or another.

1249
01:33:31,634 --> 01:33:34,125
So it died when it come out?

1250
01:33:35,438 --> 01:33:38,874
My daddy, he come out
there to the shed and got me

1251
01:33:38,941 --> 01:33:41,569
and said, "Here, take
this and throw it away,"

1252
01:33:41,644 --> 01:33:46,081
and he handed me a towel
with something or other in it.

1253
01:33:48,117 --> 01:33:53,919
I started for that barrel, and... I opened
up the towel to see what was in there,

1254
01:33:53,990 --> 01:33:59,223
'cause there was a noise and
something moving around in it.

1255
01:33:59,295 --> 01:34:03,732
That towel was all bloody-like,
all around it there.

1256
01:34:08,137 --> 01:34:12,437
It was a little old baby,
not no bigger than a squirrel.

1257
01:34:13,209 --> 01:34:15,268
It was alive?

1258
01:34:15,344 --> 01:34:18,006
Yes, sir. Right then it was.

1259
01:34:19,682 --> 01:34:22,480
A boy or a girl?

1260
01:34:22,551 --> 01:34:24,883
It was a little old boy.

1261
01:34:26,889 --> 01:34:29,323
You threw it in the trash barrel?

1262
01:34:30,026 --> 01:34:32,859
Well, that didn't seem right to me,

1263
01:34:32,928 --> 01:34:35,226
so I went in there in the
shed and got a shoe box

1264
01:34:35,297 --> 01:34:41,167
and emptied out the screwdrivers and
washers and nuts and things out of it.

1265
01:34:41,237 --> 01:34:44,502
I taken the little fella
and put him in the box,

1266
01:34:44,573 --> 01:34:48,065
buried him out there in
the corner of the yard.

1267
01:34:48,144 --> 01:34:51,113
That seemed more proper to me, I reckon.

1268
01:34:51,914 --> 01:34:55,509
It was still alive when you buried it?

1269
01:34:55,584 --> 01:34:59,179
I heard it a-cryin' a
little through that box.

1270
01:35:03,592 --> 01:35:07,460
That don't seem right. It seems like you
would have kept him and took care of him

1271
01:35:07,530 --> 01:35:09,555
if he was your brother.

1272
01:35:09,632 --> 01:35:15,161
I wasn't but six or eight. I
reckon I didn't know what to do.

1273
01:35:15,237 --> 01:35:18,502
I didn't know how to care for no baby.

1274
01:35:18,574 --> 01:35:21,668
My mother and father didn't want him.

1275
01:35:22,578 --> 01:35:25,843
They learned me to do
what they told me to do.

1276
01:35:26,649 --> 01:35:28,844
These days I figure it was probably best

1277
01:35:28,918 --> 01:35:33,855
we just give him right back to the
Good Lord right off the bat anyhow.

1278
01:35:34,290 --> 01:35:36,781
That makes me feel real sad.

1279
01:35:37,860 --> 01:35:40,158
Couldn't you have done something, Karl?

1280
01:35:40,229 --> 01:35:42,720
I would have. I wish I'd had him.

1281
01:35:42,798 --> 01:35:44,891
He'd still be right here now.

1282
01:35:44,967 --> 01:35:46,696
Living.

1283
01:35:48,037 --> 01:35:50,369
It makes me sad, too.

1284
01:35:51,006 --> 01:35:55,340
I wish there was something
I could have did about it.

1285
01:35:57,079 --> 01:36:01,413
I don't think nothing bad
oughta happen to children.

1286
01:36:01,484 --> 01:36:05,648
I think all the old bad things ought to be
saved up for the folks that done growed up.

1287
01:36:05,721 --> 01:36:08,212
That's the way I see it. Mm-hm.

1288
01:36:11,360 --> 01:36:14,488
I shouldn't have told you about that.

1289
01:36:14,563 --> 01:36:18,021
A boy your age ought
not to hear such things.

1290
01:36:18,100 --> 01:36:20,261
It just kinda come out.

1291
01:36:21,070 --> 01:36:23,937
I didn't mean to say
nothing bad about you.

1292
01:36:24,006 --> 01:36:26,839
You're good. You don't mean no harm.

1293
01:36:28,144 --> 01:36:33,878
Did you ever think about killing
yourself on purpose, like Daddy did?

1294
01:36:35,317 --> 01:36:37,649
I've studied about it some.

1295
01:36:38,654 --> 01:36:41,145
The Bible says you ought not to.

1296
01:36:42,625 --> 01:36:46,061
Says if you do that,
you go out to Hades.

1297
01:36:46,128 --> 01:36:50,428
Some folks call it hell,
I call it Hades. Mm-hm.

1298
01:36:50,499 --> 01:36:54,936
Bible says the same thing
about killing others, too.

1299
01:37:03,946 --> 01:37:06,278
Yes, sir, I reckon it does.

1300
01:37:22,965 --> 01:37:25,092
(Doorbell)

1301
01:37:25,167 --> 01:37:28,068
I always get nervous
when I hear that doorbell.

1302
01:37:28,137 --> 01:37:32,631
I'm OK walking over here, but there's
something about that dang doorbell.

1303
01:37:32,708 --> 01:37:36,542
They have one room where you can't walk
on the carpet or sit on the furniture.

1304
01:37:36,612 --> 01:37:39,513
I don't see much sense in having it.

1305
01:37:44,453 --> 01:37:47,286
Son, why you keep on coming over here

1306
01:37:47,356 --> 01:37:49,756
and you know these folks
don't want you here?

1307
01:37:49,825 --> 01:37:52,225
They run you away every time.

1308
01:37:52,294 --> 01:37:56,253
Don't keep doing this to
yourself. You's a sweet boy.

1309
01:37:56,332 --> 01:38:00,428
Why don't you go and give them flowers
to somebody that's gonna enjoy 'em?

1310
01:38:00,502 --> 01:38:03,528
Ma'am, I really wanna
give them to Karen.

1311
01:38:06,108 --> 01:38:08,406
You his daddy?

1312
01:38:08,477 --> 01:38:10,911
No, ma'am.

1313
01:38:10,980 --> 01:38:14,108
Well, whoever you are, you need
to try to talk some sense into him.

1314
01:38:14,183 --> 01:38:19,246
That little old girl is too fast for
him, and she don't wanna see him no way.

1315
01:38:19,321 --> 01:38:22,620
Will you get her for me,
please? I really wanna see her.

1316
01:38:22,691 --> 01:38:25,683
She'll want to see me, too,
'cause we're not in public.

1317
01:38:25,761 --> 01:38:29,060
Just don't tell her folks that I'm here.

1318
01:38:31,967 --> 01:38:33,958
OK.

1319
01:38:50,185 --> 01:38:53,882
Hey, Frank, you shouldn't be coming over
here. My parents really don't want you to.

1320
01:38:53,956 --> 01:38:57,585
I wanted to bring you some
flowers. They're pretty good ones.

1321
01:38:57,660 --> 01:38:59,890
They're from the Dollar
Store. I'm not an idiot.

1322
01:38:59,962 --> 01:39:03,227
Besides, we have a
garden full of flowers.

1323
01:39:03,299 --> 01:39:06,325
And I wanted you to meet
Karl. He's my new friend,

1324
01:39:06,402 --> 01:39:08,529
but it seems like I've always known him.

1325
01:39:08,604 --> 01:39:10,902
I thought you should meet him.

1326
01:39:10,973 --> 01:39:12,531
Hi, Karl.

1327
01:39:12,608 --> 01:39:14,542
Pleased to meet you.

1328
01:39:14,610 --> 01:39:16,874
He'll be around for a long time,

1329
01:39:16,946 --> 01:39:19,244
and I hope you will too, so...

1330
01:39:19,315 --> 01:39:23,809
Here. Give me the flowers. I'll do
something with them. Now you better go.

1331
01:39:23,886 --> 01:39:28,118
Maybe I'll see you down at the secret
place one day in a week or two or something.

1332
01:39:28,190 --> 01:39:32,627
I have a boyfriend now, you know, and
we're pretty serious. He gave me a ring.

1333
01:39:32,695 --> 01:39:35,186
Can you go with us
now? With me and Karl?

1334
01:39:35,264 --> 01:39:37,994
We could just hang out.
He has some cool books.

1335
01:39:38,067 --> 01:39:41,696
Frank, I just like you as a friend,
and only at the secret place.

1336
01:39:41,770 --> 01:39:44,898
I can't go there now.
I'll see you later.

1337
01:39:44,974 --> 01:39:47,670
- But just for a while.
- I'm closing the door now.

1338
01:39:48,610 --> 01:39:51,101
I told you, I'll see you later.

1339
01:39:56,852 --> 01:40:00,879
She said she'd see me later.
That's kinda good, right?

1340
01:40:00,956 --> 01:40:03,117
I reckon.

1341
01:40:06,695 --> 01:40:08,686
Well, hell, there's the boys.

1342
01:40:08,764 --> 01:40:12,723
How are you doing, boys?
I'm glad y'all came back.

1343
01:40:12,801 --> 01:40:16,168
I was wanting to talk to y'all,
too. Come over here and sit down.

1344
01:40:16,238 --> 01:40:18,331
Come on, sit down.

1345
01:40:18,407 --> 01:40:24,004
I was just telling Linda... We were, uh,
thinking that things would be a lot better

1346
01:40:24,079 --> 01:40:27,207
if I spent a lot more time over here,

1347
01:40:27,282 --> 01:40:29,807
and that we could...

1348
01:40:29,885 --> 01:40:32,080
Oh, hell, I'll just start over.

1349
01:40:32,154 --> 01:40:35,146
See, I took off work early today, and
your momma was good enough to do the same

1350
01:40:35,224 --> 01:40:37,784
so that we could talk.

1351
01:40:37,860 --> 01:40:41,159
Really, what I come over
here to do was apologize -

1352
01:40:41,230 --> 01:40:43,391
which ain't easy for me -

1353
01:40:43,465 --> 01:40:46,025
about how I acted the other night.

1354
01:40:46,969 --> 01:40:49,130
Now, I admit it, I was drunk.

1355
01:40:49,938 --> 01:40:53,874
I got all worked up, and
one thing led to another.

1356
01:40:54,910 --> 01:40:58,311
I care about y'all,
though. I do, really.

1357
01:40:59,381 --> 01:41:02,145
And I don't mean to be so damned...

1358
01:41:03,185 --> 01:41:06,780
well, asshole-ish, I
guess would be the word.

1359
01:41:07,623 --> 01:41:10,353
Karl, I don't believe I hit you, did I?

1360
01:41:10,426 --> 01:41:13,452
So no apology necessary, I guess.

1361
01:41:13,529 --> 01:41:15,895
But Frankie, I'm sorry.

1362
01:41:15,964 --> 01:41:18,194
I'm sorry I hit your momma.

1363
01:41:19,168 --> 01:41:21,602
It's just that I'm jealous of her.

1364
01:41:22,471 --> 01:41:25,531
I don't like her life
or how she lives it.

1365
01:41:26,475 --> 01:41:30,605
I don't like homosexuals, and she
goes out and buddies up with one,

1366
01:41:30,679 --> 01:41:33,239
so now I gotta deal with that.

1367
01:41:33,315 --> 01:41:36,341
I don't like little wimpy-ass
kids or mental retards,

1368
01:41:36,418 --> 01:41:40,320
and she's got one of
each living with her.

1369
01:41:40,389 --> 01:41:43,381
I'm just kidding really about that.

1370
01:41:44,359 --> 01:41:50,059
I mean, we all gotta get along, I guess,
no matter what our differences are.

1371
01:41:50,132 --> 01:41:52,464
See, I work construction.

1372
01:41:52,534 --> 01:41:54,502
I build things.

1373
01:41:54,570 --> 01:41:59,234
Do you understand how important
that is to the world, Frankie?

1374
01:41:59,308 --> 01:42:03,768
I don't know if y'all realize the
pressure a man like me's got on him.

1375
01:42:05,080 --> 01:42:08,777
Well, the upshot is, I'm gonna
be spending a lot more time here.

1376
01:42:08,851 --> 01:42:13,117
We're gonna all get along
like a family should.

1377
01:42:13,188 --> 01:42:17,682
I might even surprise you,
honey, and pop the question.

1378
01:42:21,563 --> 01:42:23,724
Well,

1379
01:42:23,799 --> 01:42:29,032
I'm gonna get on back over to the job
site, lock up some stuff over there.

1380
01:42:29,104 --> 01:42:35,339
I just wanted to stop by and... give
y'all some little piece of happiness today.

1381
01:42:35,410 --> 01:42:38,174
Bye-bye, sweetie.

1382
01:42:38,247 --> 01:42:40,340
Karl.

1383
01:42:40,415 --> 01:42:42,406
Frankie,

1384
01:42:42,484 --> 01:42:45,282
you be a good boy, now, you hear me?

1385
01:42:51,894 --> 01:42:57,127
Well, at least he's trying.
But who knows for how long?

1386
01:42:58,333 --> 01:43:02,201
He's lying, Momma.
He'll never do better.

1387
01:43:02,271 --> 01:43:04,432
I know, honey.

1388
01:43:06,141 --> 01:43:09,440
Just remember what I
said. We'll bide our time.

1389
01:43:09,511 --> 01:43:13,470
You just steer clear of
him as much as you can.

1390
01:43:13,549 --> 01:43:18,452
Doyle's had a real hard life. It's
just about run him crazy, I think.

1391
01:43:18,520 --> 01:43:21,182
We've had hard lives, too, Momma.

1392
01:43:24,193 --> 01:43:26,593
You're a hell of a boy, Frank.

1393
01:43:28,397 --> 01:43:33,391
Someday you're gonna get all
the good things you deserve.

1394
01:43:33,468 --> 01:43:39,236
Karl here's gonna get some more biscuits
tonight. What do you think about that?

1395
01:43:39,308 --> 01:43:41,640
I could sure use some.

1396
01:43:49,418 --> 01:43:53,548
Hey, there, Karl. Come
unload a generator for me.

1397
01:44:04,299 --> 01:44:08,326
Karl, lift this thing down and carry it
to the back for me. It's on the blink.

1398
01:44:08,403 --> 01:44:10,030
Say, you want us to
help you lift that thing?

1399
01:44:10,105 --> 01:44:15,372
Oh, no. That Karl's strong enough to lift
a bulldozer. He can fix anything, too.

1400
01:44:15,444 --> 01:44:19,710
I tell you, he's mentally retarded,
but he's a whiz with small engines.

1401
01:44:19,781 --> 01:44:22,807
I tell you, the Lord
works in mysterious ways.

1402
01:44:22,884 --> 01:44:26,547
So, anyway, what I was telling you
was, he didn't just make the team,

1403
01:44:26,622 --> 01:44:30,149
coach says he's going to
start him at end on defense.

1404
01:44:30,225 --> 01:44:33,160
There's a chip off the old
block, ain't you, Steve?

1405
01:44:33,228 --> 01:44:34,217
Yeah, I guess so.

1406
01:44:34,296 --> 01:44:36,389
(Bill) And how's the rest of
the team looking this year?

1407
01:44:36,465 --> 01:44:38,729
Pretty good. Pretty good.
We expect to do well.

1408
01:44:38,800 --> 01:44:41,064
- (Bill) You got any quarterback this year?
- (Walter) Pretty good.

1409
01:44:41,136 --> 01:44:43,832
Jeff Bailey's boy, you know him.
Got a good arm, a little slow.

1410
01:44:43,905 --> 01:44:46,738
(Bill) Yeah, I watched him in junior high.
He can... he can throw the ball pretty well.

1411
01:44:46,808 --> 01:44:50,209
He's taller than he was then. But
you're gonna start at the defensive end?

1412
01:44:53,649 --> 01:44:55,173
Hey, boy.

1413
01:44:55,250 --> 01:44:57,241
Hey.

1414
01:44:58,820 --> 01:45:03,553
- What are you reading?
- Book on how to work carpentry.

1415
01:45:03,625 --> 01:45:07,891
I aim to learn how to make
things out of wood some day.

1416
01:45:07,963 --> 01:45:10,932
Cabinets and whatnot.

1417
01:45:10,999 --> 01:45:16,027
These drawings in here, they
don't make no sense to me so far.

1418
01:45:18,240 --> 01:45:21,141
You look like your tail's
kinda dragging a mite.

1419
01:45:21,209 --> 01:45:23,700
You got something wrong with you?

1420
01:45:23,779 --> 01:45:27,044
Seems like Doyle's made his way in.

1421
01:45:27,115 --> 01:45:32,553
Momma said he's staying over tonight, and
he's talking about staying here for good.

1422
01:45:32,621 --> 01:45:38,218
We ain't ever gonna be happy. We'll
always stay nervous, won't we, Karl?

1423
01:45:39,027 --> 01:45:41,359
I don't reckon I know, boy.

1424
01:45:42,331 --> 01:45:45,164
I ain't never found no
way to not be nervous.

1425
01:45:45,233 --> 01:45:48,532
I'm three or four
times as old as you are.

1426
01:45:50,238 --> 01:45:53,139
Maybe that's just the way folks is.

1427
01:45:53,975 --> 01:45:57,138
I feel sad about Karen Cross, too.

1428
01:45:57,212 --> 01:46:00,807
I just make like to
myself that she loves me.

1429
01:46:02,017 --> 01:46:03,985
I know better, though,

1430
01:46:04,052 --> 01:46:07,351
but it just feels
good when I imagine it.

1431
01:46:08,590 --> 01:46:14,426
Making believe always made me feel
pretty good too, from time to time.

1432
01:46:22,604 --> 01:46:25,630
Bill Cox is going to a funeral
for a Mr. Turner tomorrow

1433
01:46:25,707 --> 01:46:28,198
and closing up shop early. Mm-hm.

1434
01:46:28,243 --> 01:46:30,575
- Is that right?
- Yes, sir.

1435
01:46:33,782 --> 01:46:36,580
I figured I'd play ball with you.

1436
01:46:38,520 --> 01:46:41,114
You will? For sure?

1437
01:46:41,189 --> 01:46:43,885
Yes, sir. Well, I figure if
neither one of us is no account,

1438
01:46:43,959 --> 01:46:46,325
it won't make no difference, will it?

1439
01:46:46,395 --> 01:46:47,623
Yeah.

1440
01:46:47,696 --> 01:46:50,187
You wanna be on teams, me and you?

1441
01:46:50,232 --> 01:46:51,631
Yes, sir.

1442
01:46:51,700 --> 01:46:53,065
All right, then.

1443
01:46:53,301 --> 01:46:55,462
All right, then.

1444
01:46:58,173 --> 01:47:00,164
Hup!

1445
01:47:01,042 --> 01:47:03,602
Come on, man.

1446
01:47:09,184 --> 01:47:11,880
Good job, Karl. We got a touchdown.

1447
01:47:12,687 --> 01:47:14,587
That was a good lateral, man.

1448
01:47:14,656 --> 01:47:17,819
That was just like the wishbone.

1449
01:47:17,893 --> 01:47:21,693
Yes, sir. Well, I darn
near made me a touchdown.

1450
01:47:21,763 --> 01:47:25,529
Then I seen them boys bearing down on me,
figured I'd better give it off to you there.

1451
01:47:25,600 --> 01:47:27,568
I seen you following me. Mm-hm.

1452
01:47:27,636 --> 01:47:31,163
Yeah. We're liable to
win if we keep this up.

1453
01:47:31,239 --> 01:47:34,299
For somebody like you,
you sure can run fast.

1454
01:47:34,376 --> 01:47:38,176
- Come on, let's kick off to 'em.
- All right, then.

1455
01:47:42,884 --> 01:47:45,580
I know you could've scored
that touchdown by yourself

1456
01:47:45,654 --> 01:47:48,384
instead of just throwing it over to me.

1457
01:47:48,957 --> 01:47:52,017
Them boys was trying to
pull me down pretty hard.

1458
01:47:52,093 --> 01:47:54,926
You're strong, though. You
just threw it over to me

1459
01:47:54,996 --> 01:47:57,863
where I could score that
touchdown so I'd feel good.

1460
01:47:57,933 --> 01:48:01,027
My daddy used to do that kind of thing.

1461
01:48:03,705 --> 01:48:06,833
It don't matter to me about
us losing. Does it to you?

1462
01:48:06,908 --> 01:48:08,637
No, sir.

1463
01:48:08,710 --> 01:48:10,644
It was fun anyhow.

1464
01:48:10,712 --> 01:48:15,274
I wasn't thinking about nothing
else, just like you told me I'd do.

1465
01:48:15,350 --> 01:48:17,841
Can we play every Saturday?

1466
01:48:17,919 --> 01:48:19,910
If I ain't too stoved up.

1467
01:48:19,988 --> 01:48:23,185
I ain't like you. I'm old and give out.

1468
01:48:26,094 --> 01:48:28,426
I'm proud of you.

1469
01:50:25,480 --> 01:50:27,471
(Muttering.)

1470
01:50:43,732 --> 01:50:46,462
Kick your head in 25 years ago.

1471
01:50:46,534 --> 01:50:49,833
You're dead, I guess. Where'd you go to?

1472
01:50:53,108 --> 01:50:55,099
(Muttering.)

1473
01:51:00,081 --> 01:51:02,072
(Chuckling.)

1474
01:51:09,958 --> 01:51:12,119
I'm your boy.

1475
01:51:15,263 --> 01:51:17,595
I ain't got no boy.

1476
01:51:20,435 --> 01:51:23,370
I'm your oldest boy, name of Karl.

1477
01:51:23,438 --> 01:51:25,770
I ain't got no boy.

1478
01:51:28,543 --> 01:51:34,482
They turned me loose from the nervous
hospital, said I was well. Mm-hm.

1479
01:51:42,257 --> 01:51:48,594
I got hired on to work for a Mr. Bill
Cox, fixing lawn mowers and whatnot. Mm-hm.

1480
01:51:50,799 --> 01:51:54,462
That grass out there in the
yard, it's growed up quite a bit.

1481
01:51:54,536 --> 01:51:58,199
I figured I might
cut it for you. Mm-hm.

1482
01:51:58,273 --> 01:52:03,370
I told you, I ain't got no boy. Now, why
don't you get on outta here and let me be?

1483
01:52:03,445 --> 01:52:06,312
You ain't no kin to me.

1484
01:52:09,684 --> 01:52:12,016
I learned to read some.

1485
01:52:15,724 --> 01:52:18,056
I read the Bible quite a bit.

1486
01:52:24,099 --> 01:52:29,901
I can't understand all of it, but I
reckon I understand a good deal of it.

1487
01:52:29,971 --> 01:52:34,101
Them stories you and Momma
told me, they ain't in there.

1488
01:52:36,077 --> 01:52:38,910
You oughta not done that to your boy.

1489
01:52:41,015 --> 01:52:43,950
I've studied on killing you.

1490
01:52:44,786 --> 01:52:47,277
I studied about it quite a bit.

1491
01:52:51,926 --> 01:52:53,723
But I don't reckon
there's no need for it

1492
01:52:53,795 --> 01:52:57,663
if all you're gonna do is
sit there in that chair.

1493
01:52:57,732 --> 01:53:00,530
You'll be dead soon enough,

1494
01:53:00,602 --> 01:53:03,196
and the world'll be shut of you.

1495
01:53:11,446 --> 01:53:14,745
You oughta not killed my little brother.

1496
01:53:17,452 --> 01:53:20,853
He ought to have had
a chance to growed up.

1497
01:53:22,690 --> 01:53:25,386
He would have had fun sometimes.

1498
01:53:59,727 --> 01:54:01,888
Little fella.

1499
01:55:10,698 --> 01:55:13,189
- (Gasps.)
- Hey!

1500
01:55:13,268 --> 01:55:16,101
What in the goddamn
hell are you doing, Karl?

1501
01:55:16,170 --> 01:55:18,035
What the fuck are you doing
up in the middle of the night?

1502
01:55:18,106 --> 01:55:21,940
- What do you want, hon?
- I wanna be baptized.

1503
01:55:22,010 --> 01:55:24,570
(Doyle.) Well, get baptized,
then. I don't give a shit.

1504
01:55:24,646 --> 01:55:28,047
Call up a fucking preacher,
goddamnit! We can't baptize you.

1505
01:55:28,116 --> 01:55:31,711
We'll call Brother Epersom. We'll go
see him tomorrow and get you baptized.

1506
01:55:31,786 --> 01:55:34,983
It's Sunday. You go on back to bed, now.

1507
01:55:36,991 --> 01:55:40,392
What are you doing
with that damn hammer?

1508
01:55:43,264 --> 01:55:47,701
I don't rightly know. I just
kinda woke up a-holdin' it.

1509
01:55:55,777 --> 01:55:57,472
What the fuck do you think
he's doing with that hammer?

1510
01:55:57,545 --> 01:55:59,706
I don't know.

1511
01:56:01,282 --> 01:56:03,273
(Sighs.)

1512
01:56:20,768 --> 01:56:25,205
Upon his profession of faith in
our Lord and Savior Jesus Christ,

1513
01:56:25,273 --> 01:56:27,833
and in obedience under his command,

1514
01:56:27,909 --> 01:56:30,139
and by the authority of the Church,

1515
01:56:30,211 --> 01:56:33,442
I indeed baptize this my brother

1516
01:56:33,514 --> 01:56:38,247
in the name of the Father, and
the Son, and the Holy Ghost.

1517
01:56:41,723 --> 01:56:43,554
Amen.

1518
01:56:43,624 --> 01:56:46,491
Marie, would you sing 137, please?

1519
01:56:47,295 --> 01:56:50,856
Softly and tenderly

1520
01:56:50,932 --> 01:56:54,595
Jesus is calling

1521
01:56:54,669 --> 01:57:00,266
Calling for you and for me

1522
01:57:02,377 --> 01:57:04,538
- Hi.
- Hi.

1523
01:57:05,713 --> 01:57:08,614
- So how'd the baptizing go?
- It went real good.

1524
01:57:08,683 --> 01:57:10,844
Yeah? Good.

1525
01:57:11,786 --> 01:57:13,947
I'm kinda hungry.

1526
01:57:14,022 --> 01:57:16,650
Ain't it about time to eat?

1527
01:57:16,724 --> 01:57:20,820
You know what I got a craving
for? Some of that Chicken Champ.

1528
01:57:20,895 --> 01:57:23,489
Why don't you run down
there and get some? I'll buy.

1529
01:57:23,564 --> 01:57:27,466
- Would y'all like that?
- It sure sounds fine to me.

1530
01:57:27,535 --> 01:57:30,197
I'd have me a chicken
leg or two. Mm-hm.

1531
01:57:32,974 --> 01:57:37,240
- Get some of their coleslaw, too.
- OK. All right, y'all wanna go with me?

1532
01:57:37,311 --> 01:57:39,711
No, they don't need to go with
you. There's a ball game coming on.

1533
01:57:39,781 --> 01:57:43,842
- We'll just sit here and do man things.
- I'll be back in a little bit, then.

1534
01:57:43,918 --> 01:57:47,513
- All right. Hey, get some extra gravy.
- OK.

1535
01:57:52,193 --> 01:57:55,720
Why don't y'all sit
your asses down here?

1536
01:57:55,797 --> 01:57:57,958
Sit down.

1537
01:58:10,244 --> 01:58:16,240
I just wanted to get your momma outta the
house for a few minutes so we could talk.

1538
01:58:25,927 --> 01:58:28,327
See, here's the deal, Frank.

1539
01:58:30,932 --> 01:58:36,802
If I'm gonna throw my life away doing
what I want to come live with y'all,

1540
01:58:36,871 --> 01:58:39,704
we're gonna get some shit straight.

1541
01:58:39,774 --> 01:58:43,904
See, your mommy and I don't
have no problems except for you.

1542
01:58:43,978 --> 01:58:47,379
Fact is, we'd never have
a bad word between us.

1543
01:58:47,448 --> 01:58:49,609
But since you do exist,

1544
01:58:49,684 --> 01:58:52,551
and I'm gonna be the
head of the household,

1545
01:58:52,620 --> 01:58:55,054
then you're gonna learn
to live by my rules.

1546
01:58:55,690 --> 01:58:59,148
And the first rule is, you don't
speak unless you're spoken to.

1547
01:58:59,227 --> 01:59:01,718
You got me?

1548
01:59:01,796 --> 01:59:04,356
Now, you stay the hell outta my way.

1549
01:59:05,166 --> 01:59:07,691
And do what a regular kid does.

1550
01:59:07,768 --> 01:59:11,534
You're a weird little shit,
Frank, and I don't get you.

1551
01:59:11,606 --> 01:59:13,767
So wake up,

1552
01:59:13,841 --> 01:59:16,332
and face what they call reality.

1553
01:59:17,044 --> 01:59:21,538
See, we're gonna be a
family, Frank. My family.

1554
01:59:21,616 --> 01:59:24,210
I'll be paying all the bills,

1555
01:59:24,285 --> 01:59:27,277
so that means you're stuck with my ass.

1556
01:59:27,355 --> 01:59:30,119
But I ain't your daddy.

1557
01:59:30,191 --> 01:59:32,785
You just act like I am.

1558
01:59:32,860 --> 01:59:37,695
And the other thing I say is,
your buddy Karl here's going.

1559
01:59:38,633 --> 01:59:41,158
We can't be no normal family
with him living in the garage

1560
01:59:41,235 --> 01:59:44,261
and coming into the damn bedroom at four
in the morning carrying hammers and shit.

1561
01:59:44,338 --> 01:59:46,829
Karl can stay if he
wants to. Momma said...

1562
01:59:46,908 --> 01:59:48,671
What did I tell you about your momma?

1563
01:59:48,743 --> 01:59:53,373
Mister, don't you never lay another
hand on that boy. You understand me?

1564
01:59:53,447 --> 01:59:56,712
Let go of my goddamn hand, you retard.
Now get out there and get your shit,

1565
01:59:56,784 --> 01:59:58,945
and get out.

1566
02:00:00,955 --> 02:00:03,947
That was a wake-up call, Frankie.

1567
02:00:04,025 --> 02:00:07,358
You remember what I said
about reality, Frank.

1568
02:00:07,428 --> 02:00:09,589
Get out, retard.

1569
02:01:07,088 --> 02:01:10,854
Where are you going, Karl? Didn't
you want some chicken and things?

1570
02:01:10,925 --> 02:01:14,190
No, ma'am. I'm going off somewheres.

1571
02:01:14,262 --> 02:01:17,095
Well, OK. I got you some.

1572
02:01:17,164 --> 02:01:19,291
That Frank, he went off somewheres too,

1573
02:01:19,367 --> 02:01:21,892
so when you go in there,
he won't be indoors.

1574
02:01:21,969 --> 02:01:23,834
Where'd he go? What's going on?

1575
02:01:23,904 --> 02:01:26,668
He just wanted to go
off and play, I reckon.

1576
02:01:26,741 --> 02:01:31,474
You just go in there and eat your dinner
with that Doyle. Don't worry yourself none.

1577
02:01:31,545 --> 02:01:33,445
All right, then.

1578
02:01:33,514 --> 02:01:37,678
Well, I'll see you later. Oh, if you
see Frank, tell him to come on back home.

1579
02:01:37,752 --> 02:01:42,553
I don't get to see him all day except
Sundays. He can go play tomorrow.

1580
02:01:42,623 --> 02:01:44,784
- Ma'am?
- Yeah.

1581
02:01:48,629 --> 02:01:51,689
You're a good momma to that boy.

1582
02:01:51,766 --> 02:01:53,859
You care for him.

1583
02:01:53,934 --> 02:01:56,869
You work hard to care for him.

1584
02:01:56,937 --> 02:01:59,735
You light him up in his eyes,

1585
02:01:59,807 --> 02:02:01,798
I've seen it.

1586
02:02:02,743 --> 02:02:06,372
That boy wouldn't know
what to do without you.

1587
02:02:06,447 --> 02:02:09,075
Well, thank you, hon. That's
real good of you to say.

1588
02:02:09,150 --> 02:02:11,778
I wouldn't know what to
do without him either.

1589
02:02:11,852 --> 02:02:14,446
You've been real good to me, too.

1590
02:02:14,522 --> 02:02:19,016
It ain't everybody that'd make
biscuits in the middle of the night.

1591
02:02:19,093 --> 02:02:22,927
You and that boy has
given me a good feeling.

1592
02:02:22,997 --> 02:02:25,591
We sure like having you.

1593
02:02:25,666 --> 02:02:27,827
Thank you.

1594
02:02:29,370 --> 02:02:32,430
I'm just now getting
around to telling you,

1595
02:02:32,506 --> 02:02:36,943
but I fixed that washing machine so that
boy ain't gotta tote that laundry no more.

1596
02:02:37,011 --> 02:02:39,036
Oh, thank you.

1597
02:02:39,113 --> 02:02:41,104
Thanks.

1598
02:02:44,952 --> 02:02:47,284
You been real good to me.

1599
02:02:55,896 --> 02:02:58,160
Karl?

1600
02:03:04,305 --> 02:03:07,468
Hey, Karl. How'd you
know to come out here?

1601
02:03:07,541 --> 02:03:09,873
I knowed you'd be out here.

1602
02:03:10,845 --> 02:03:13,439
What are you doing
digging with that stub?

1603
02:03:13,514 --> 02:03:16,745
Just digging. I ain't
ever gonna be happy now.

1604
02:03:16,817 --> 02:03:20,275
Not with that son of a
bitch moving in for good.

1605
02:03:20,354 --> 02:03:23,221
I wish me and you and
Momma would just run away,

1606
02:03:23,290 --> 02:03:25,622
but she said...

1607
02:03:25,693 --> 02:03:28,093
wherever we went, he'd find us.

1608
02:03:28,162 --> 02:03:34,465
He's crazy. Sometimes I think it'd have
been better off if I wasn't even born.

1609
02:03:34,535 --> 02:03:37,436
Well, I'm glad of it you was borned.

1610
02:03:39,940 --> 02:03:43,740
I don't reckon I'm gonna be
out there in the garage no more.

1611
02:03:43,811 --> 02:03:46,507
You have to, Karl. You
have to look out for me.

1612
02:03:46,580 --> 02:03:49,344
You can't let that son
of a bitch run you off.

1613
02:03:49,417 --> 02:03:54,855
You're just a boy. You ought
not to use language like that.

1614
02:03:54,922 --> 02:03:57,447
I don't mean to say
nothing bad about you,

1615
02:03:57,525 --> 02:04:02,360
but why don't you stop Doyle
when he's being thataway?

1616
02:04:02,430 --> 02:04:06,457
You're older than him.
You're strong, too.

1617
02:04:06,534 --> 02:04:10,561
My daddy wouldn't let him
do that to me and Momma.

1618
02:04:12,339 --> 02:04:15,240
That fella's a whole
sight meaner than me.

1619
02:04:15,309 --> 02:04:17,641
He'd just whup the tar outta me.

1620
02:04:17,711 --> 02:04:19,042
Yeah.

1621
02:04:19,113 --> 02:04:21,206
I guess so.

1622
02:04:22,016 --> 02:04:24,507
I'm real tired, you know that?

1623
02:04:25,519 --> 02:04:28,920
A boy my age shouldn't
be tired of things.

1624
02:04:31,826 --> 02:04:33,987
I'm tired, too.

1625
02:04:36,831 --> 02:04:40,858
Just 'cause I ain't gonna
be around no more maybe,

1626
02:04:40,935 --> 02:04:43,495
it don't mean I don't care for you.

1627
02:04:43,571 --> 02:04:46,005
I care for you a good deal.

1628
02:04:46,073 --> 02:04:48,940
I care for you more than
anything else there is.

1629
02:04:49,009 --> 02:04:52,706
You and me made friends
right off the bat.

1630
02:04:52,780 --> 02:04:57,547
I care for you, too. But you'll
be around. Don't say that.

1631
02:04:57,618 --> 02:05:01,110
It don't make no difference
where I was to be.

1632
02:05:01,188 --> 02:05:03,179
We'll always be friends.

1633
02:05:03,257 --> 02:05:05,555
Can't nobody stop that.

1634
02:05:15,803 --> 02:05:19,034
I aim for you to have these books.

1635
02:05:19,106 --> 02:05:22,007
You don't wanna give
away all your books.

1636
02:05:22,076 --> 02:05:24,408
I aim for you to have 'em.

1637
02:05:32,987 --> 02:05:37,151
Maybe you can make a little
more sense outta 'em than I can.

1638
02:05:37,224 --> 02:05:43,220
I made you a little old book marker and
put it in there in that book on Christmas.

1639
02:05:44,265 --> 02:05:46,028
Man.

1640
02:05:46,100 --> 02:05:48,091
Thanks.

1641
02:05:49,837 --> 02:05:53,500
You know when you get a
feeling and you don't know why?

1642
02:05:53,574 --> 02:05:56,168
Yes, sir.

1643
02:05:56,243 --> 02:05:58,575
I got a feeling today.

1644
02:05:59,780 --> 02:06:02,078
Reckon what kind of a feeling?

1645
02:06:02,983 --> 02:06:06,384
Like something different. I don't know.

1646
02:06:08,923 --> 02:06:11,721
You're leaving, ain't you, Karl?

1647
02:06:20,935 --> 02:06:24,427
Would you do something for
me if was to I ask you to?

1648
02:06:24,505 --> 02:06:27,497
You know I would. Whatever you want.

1649
02:06:30,210 --> 02:06:32,405
When you leave outta here tonight,

1650
02:06:32,479 --> 02:06:37,109
I don't want you going over
and staying with that Doyle.

1651
02:06:38,819 --> 02:06:43,688
He's got it out for you
tonight. I got me a feeling, too.

1652
02:06:43,757 --> 02:06:47,591
You oughta not be over there when
he's all liquored up and mean thataway.

1653
02:06:47,661 --> 02:06:49,720
Your momma neither.

1654
02:06:50,664 --> 02:06:55,158
When you get up from here to leave, I
want you to go over to that fella's house.

1655
02:06:55,235 --> 02:06:57,396
Your momma's friend.

1656
02:07:00,240 --> 02:07:03,300
I want you to give me your word on it.

1657
02:07:03,377 --> 02:07:06,073
OK. I give you my word on it.

1658
02:07:07,881 --> 02:07:11,578
Is everything gonna be
OK? Are you all right?

1659
02:07:15,889 --> 02:07:19,586
Yeah, everything's
gonna be all right, boy.

1660
02:07:27,067 --> 02:07:29,695
I kinda wanna put my arm
around you for a minute,

1661
02:07:29,770 --> 02:07:33,171
then I'm gonna get up
and leave outta here.

1662
02:07:33,240 --> 02:07:35,231
OK.

1663
02:08:01,201 --> 02:08:03,533
I love you, boy.

1664
02:08:05,673 --> 02:08:08,005
I love you, too.

1665
02:08:11,378 --> 02:08:13,539
All right, then.

1666
02:08:29,296 --> 02:08:30,627
Karl?

1667
02:08:54,188 --> 02:08:56,679
Karl, what are you doing
here? You want to come in?

1668
02:08:56,757 --> 02:09:01,160
I ain't a-stayin'. I need
to ask you for a favor.

1669
02:09:01,228 --> 02:09:03,355
OK.

1670
02:09:03,430 --> 02:09:06,888
This evening, I want you to
go get that Miss Wheatley,

1671
02:09:06,967 --> 02:09:11,063
let her and that Frank stay
over here with you tonight.

1672
02:09:11,138 --> 02:09:13,629
What's... What's wrong?
Is everything all right?

1673
02:09:13,674 --> 02:09:15,938
That Doyle.

1674
02:09:16,009 --> 02:09:20,673
He's in a bad way again with that
drinking and a-bein' mean to folks.

1675
02:09:20,748 --> 02:09:22,682
I want you to give me
your word you'll do it.

1676
02:09:22,750 --> 02:09:26,242
Well, sure, OK. Has... has...
He hasn't hurt them, has he?

1677
02:09:26,320 --> 02:09:28,311
No, sir, not yet.

1678
02:09:29,923 --> 02:09:31,413
Here.

1679
02:09:31,492 --> 02:09:33,858
I want you to give that
to that Miss Wheatley.

1680
02:09:33,927 --> 02:09:35,918
It ain't much.

1681
02:09:35,996 --> 02:09:39,329
But there might be a little
something there to help out.

1682
02:09:39,399 --> 02:09:44,735
It's what I made a-fixin' lawn
mowers and whatnot for Bill Cox.

1683
02:09:44,805 --> 02:09:47,797
Well, how about you, Karl?
You want to stay here?

1684
02:09:49,276 --> 02:09:54,680
I don't reckon that you have to go
with women to be a good daddy to a boy.

1685
02:09:54,748 --> 02:09:57,979
You been real square-dealing with me.

1686
02:09:58,919 --> 02:10:02,377
Bible says two men ought
not to lay together.

1687
02:10:03,457 --> 02:10:09,123
But I'll bet you the good Lord
wouldn't send nobody like you to Hades.

1688
02:10:10,597 --> 02:10:12,963
That boy, Frank,

1689
02:10:14,067 --> 02:10:17,332
he lives inside of his own heart.

1690
02:10:17,404 --> 02:10:20,202
That's a awful big place to live in.

1691
02:10:22,276 --> 02:10:24,608
You take care of that boy.

1692
02:10:28,382 --> 02:10:31,146
I will.

1693
02:10:37,424 --> 02:10:39,415
Karl?

1694
02:15:00,253 --> 02:15:02,585
Where's everybody else?

1695
02:15:09,896 --> 02:15:12,057
You seen 'em?

1696
02:15:19,139 --> 02:15:22,404
Didn't I tell you to
get moved outta here?

1697
02:15:25,912 --> 02:15:30,042
How does a fella go about
getting hold of the police?

1698
02:15:35,755 --> 02:15:38,553
You use the fucking phone, I guess.

1699
02:15:40,026 --> 02:15:42,460
Which numbers do you put in?

1700
02:15:50,470 --> 02:15:53,166
Can't you see I'm trying to relax?

1701
02:15:55,642 --> 02:15:59,874
I thought I told you to get
outta here, leave me alone.

1702
02:16:04,718 --> 02:16:08,210
What in the hell you doing
with that lawn mower blade?

1703
02:16:08,288 --> 02:16:10,620
I aim to kill you with it.

1704
02:16:24,237 --> 02:16:27,297
Well, to call the police, you push:

1705
02:16:27,374 --> 02:16:31,834

9-1-1.

1706
02:16:37,017 --> 02:16:40,180
You best tell 'em to bring an ambulance.

1707
02:16:42,856 --> 02:16:45,916
Or a hearse, if you're going to kill me.

1708
02:16:59,739 --> 02:17:01,730
Karl!

1709
02:17:45,885 --> 02:17:48,183
Yes, ma'am.

1710
02:17:48,255 --> 02:17:52,589
I need the police sent over here
to the Wheatley house. Mm-hm.

1711
02:17:54,361 --> 02:17:58,593
I've killed Doyle Hargraves
with a lawn mower blade.

1712
02:17:59,666 --> 02:18:02,965
Yes, ma'am. I'm right sure of it.

1713
02:18:03,970 --> 02:18:06,564
I hit him two good whacks with it.

1714
02:18:06,640 --> 02:18:10,667
That second 'un just plumb
near cut his head in two.

1715
02:18:14,247 --> 02:18:20,243
It's a little old white house on the
corner of Vine Street and some other street.

1716
02:18:21,354 --> 02:18:26,951
There's a truck out front says
"Doyle Hargraves Construction" on it.

1717
02:18:29,296 --> 02:18:32,265
Oh, I'll be sitting here waiting on you.

1718
02:18:33,266 --> 02:18:36,929
Doyle said, besides sending the police,

1719
02:18:37,003 --> 02:18:40,939
you might want to send
a ambulance or a hearse.

1720
02:18:43,310 --> 02:18:45,301
Thank you.

1721
02:19:48,775 --> 02:19:50,333
So.

1722
02:19:51,344 --> 02:19:54,108
Now... on the third day,

1723
02:19:55,315 --> 02:19:56,839
I, uh...

1724
02:19:56,916 --> 02:20:00,477
I washed her, 'cause she
wasn't too clean, you know?

1725
02:20:00,553 --> 02:20:03,488
Well, I got all the right spots.

1726
02:20:03,556 --> 02:20:06,821
She was the first one I ever kept for any
length of time, 'cause I get bored real easy.

1727
02:20:06,893 --> 02:20:10,294
I got a real short
attention span, you know.

1728
02:20:10,363 --> 02:20:11,853
Yeah.

1729
02:20:11,931 --> 02:20:16,925
I mean, I can't say that
she enjoyed her stay.

1730
02:20:20,206 --> 02:20:22,106
But that washcloth I put in her mouth,

1731
02:20:22,175 --> 02:20:24,837
I held in place with a
real fat piece of duct tape,

1732
02:20:24,911 --> 02:20:26,640
kept all her complaining
down to a minimum.

1733
02:20:26,713 --> 02:20:31,514
I don't really like people, you know, who talk
all the time. I like to do all the talking.

1734
02:20:31,584 --> 02:20:34,781
That's why I think I'm so fond of you.

1735
02:20:34,854 --> 02:20:38,415
'Cause you're just so
easy-going, you know?

1736
02:20:40,627 --> 02:20:45,155
Although I do sense a little
tension in you, time to time.

1737
02:20:48,101 --> 02:20:50,695
So you were out in the world, huh?

1738
02:20:52,705 --> 02:20:56,539
Did you have fun? Did you
make any acquaintances?

1739
02:20:56,609 --> 02:21:00,136
There was a boy. We made friends.

1740
02:21:00,213 --> 02:21:02,204
Yeah, I'll bet you did.

1741
02:21:05,718 --> 02:21:10,382
I mean, I was never bent that way.
I was bent the other way, you know.

1742
02:21:11,391 --> 02:21:13,382
So.

1743
02:21:14,794 --> 02:21:17,957
What was it like out there in the world?

1744
02:21:20,867 --> 02:21:23,529
It was too big.

1745
02:21:23,603 --> 02:21:24,865
Ah.

1746
02:21:25,872 --> 02:21:29,239
Well, it's not too big
in here, is it? Huh?

1747
02:21:29,309 --> 02:21:31,300
Huh?

1748
02:21:36,249 --> 02:21:38,240
You know something?

1749
02:21:39,285 --> 02:21:44,689
I feel real, uh, real generous
today. I feel like listening.

1750
02:21:46,025 --> 02:21:48,823
And I'll bet you got plenty to tell.

1751
02:21:50,597 --> 02:21:52,588
Karl?

1752
02:21:54,501 --> 02:21:56,492
Who'd you kill?

1753
02:21:58,104 --> 02:22:00,504
Was it the boy?

1754
02:22:00,573 --> 02:22:03,542
Don't you say nothing about that boy.

1755
02:22:09,949 --> 02:22:14,511
Fact of business, don't
you say another word to me.

1756
02:22:14,587 --> 02:22:17,181
I ain't listening to you no more.

1757
02:22:32,438 --> 02:22:35,430
Yeah, shh.

1758
